body:
@mloning, I agree with @juanitorduz - sliding and expanding window training/forecasting are in-principle different. The sliding window splitter predicts only from some recent part of the available training data - this can make sense if there is non-stationarity or concept drift and you do not want to "contaminate" the forecaster with older data.
@mloning, the additional point you raise is "what the method does" vs "what the method has access to, given its template". I think the template is designed to have access to all past data, but we can of course make specific methods which don't use it, e.g., due to the non-stationarity issue above.

Regarding @aiwalter's suggestion, i.e., whether the expanding window should be a modification of `SlidingWindowSplitter`, I'm not sure.
For one, it makes sense, since you could simply re-train and forget the oldest data, or not, and that can be part of the same reduction strategy.

However, there is a more general wrapper strategy, which forces the wrapped forecaster to forget the oldest data. The wrapped forecaster would not have to be a strategy that reduces to supervised prediction, but could be any forecaster. Not sure whether it is useful or too general though?
